"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"72bce3",
"children":[
"Characteristic symptoms and findings of chronic venous insufficiency or associated complications include:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"c08b68",
"children":[
"leg heaviness, tiredness"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a302d6",
"children":[
"dependent leg edema"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"eb8f6a",
"children":[
"hyperpigmentation, especially at medial ankle"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"de75e0",
"children":[
"pruritus and eczema"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"5d24d4",
"children":[
"varicose or reticular veins"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"c10d6f",
"children":[
"venous ulceration"
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_gm_s7_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"08be40",
"children":[
"First-line therapy includes compression (stockings, wraps, pumps) and leg elevation. Emollients are used for dry, itchy skin; topical glucocorticoids can be added for eczema. In addition to compression, patients with venous ulcers require debridement of devitalized tissue and simple nonadherent dressings. Antibiotics are limited to patients with suspected infection (increased pain, drainage, surrounding cellulitis)."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
